CSR Corp, PCCW, Ping An, Zijin Mining: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   N i c k   G e n t l e
-- 
2011-03-14T16:08:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-14/csr-corp-pccw-ping-an-zijin-mining-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  rose 0.4 percent to 23,345.88. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, gained 1 percent to 12,882.75.  CSR Corp. (1766 HK): China’s biggest train maker is
exploring options to build trains in  Bulgaria , Transport
Minister Alexander Tsvetkov told reporters in Sofia. Bulgaria
can offer CSR the lowest taxes in the European Union and access
to the EU’s 27-nation market, Tsvetkov said. The shares fell 1.9
percent to HK$8.09.    PCCW Ltd. (8)  (8 HK): Hong Kong’s biggest phone company said
its Internet services were restored to normal after they had
been affected by the earthquake in  Japan . Some undersea
communications cables that land in Japan were affected by the
earthquake, prompting PCCW to seek alternative cable systems,
the  Hong Kong  company said in an e-mailed statement today. The
stock climbed 0.3 percent to HK$3.39.  Ping An Insurance (Group) Co. of China (2318 HK): The
country’s second-largest insurer said it sold 272 million shares
at HK$71.50 apiece for a total of HK$19.4 billion ($2.5 billion)
to a company controlled by the family of billionaire Cheng Yu Tung, according to a statement to the Hong Kong stock exchange.
The shares were suspended today and will resume trading March
15.  Zijin Mining Group Co. (2899 HK): The gold miner said it
should not be liable for damage caused by the Sept. 21 collapse
of a tailings dam at a mine in  Guangdong province  operated by
two wholly-owned subsidiaries. The units will appoint their own
lawyers to defend a court case about the incident, which
resulted in 22 deaths. The stock advanced 1.7 percent to
HK$6.51.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 